# 1. What problem does this paper solve?

Large Language Models can generate code very well.

However, for difficult programming tasks, the first generated code is often incorrect.

Existing approaches usually generate many different solutions and select the best one.

This requires:

• Many samples

• High token cost

• Large computation

Instead of generating new code repeatedly, this paper teaches an LLM to debug its own generated code.

The idea is simple:

Write code

↓

Check it

↓

Explain it

↓

Find mistakes

↓

Fix them

↓

Repeat

This process is called SELF-DEBUGGING.

---

# 2. What methodology is used?

The paper introduces a framework called SELF-DEBUGGING.

The workflow is:

Problem

↓

Generate Code

↓

Execute Code

↓

Explain Generated Code

↓

Generate Feedback

↓

Repair Code

↓

Repeat until correct

The feedback can come from:

• Unit Test Results

• Execution Results

• Code Explanation

• Execution Trace

One important idea is **Rubber Duck Debugging**.

Instead of asking another person,

the LLM explains every line of code to itself.

During this explanation,

it discovers mistakes automatically.

No additional training is required.

Only prompting is used.

---

# 3. What results are achieved?

The framework was tested on several benchmarks.

These include:

• Spider (Text-to-SQL)

• MBPP

• TransCoder

Major findings:

• Improves coding accuracy by up to **12%**

• Improves SQL generation by **2–9%**

• Improves difficult SQL tasks by **9%**

• Requires fewer sampled solutions

• Matches or outperforms methods using 10× more generated programs

Most debugging tasks finish within **3 iterations**, even though the framework allows up to 10.

---

# 4. What are the limitations?

• Strong LLMs perform much better than weaker models.

• Debugging quality depends on execution feedback.

• Multiple iterations increase inference time.

• Requires executable code for best performance.

• Unit tests greatly improve debugging quality.

• Without execution feedback, improvements become smaller.

---

# 5. How is my research different?

SELF-DEBUGGING focuses on fixing generated code.

My dissertation focuses on recovering an entire Agentic AI Coding System after failures.

SELF-DEBUGGING repairs code.

My framework repairs the whole agent workflow.

My proposed framework includes:

• Failure Detection

• Failure Classification

• Self-Reflection

• Root Cause Analysis

• Memory of Previous Failures

• Planning New Repair Strategy

• Command Re-execution

• Recovery Evaluation

Unlike SELF-DEBUGGING, my research evaluates:

• Recovery Success Rate

• Recovery Time

• Number of Recovery Attempts

• Token Cost

• Recovery Efficiency

• Failure Recovery Rate

Therefore,

SELF-DEBUGGING becomes one important component inside my larger autonomous recovery framework.

---

# Key Takeaway

SELF-DEBUGGING proves that Large Language Models can automatically inspect, explain, debug, and repair their own generated code using execution feedback and self-explanation.

This paper provides one of the strongest foundations for building autonomous failure recovery systems for Agentic AI Coding Systems.